# Skill authoring

## Frontmatter description

In `SKILL.md` frontmatter, write `description` as a plain single-line string.

- Never use YAML block scalars (`>`, `|`, `>-`, `|-`, or variants).
- Keep descriptions short.
  They load on every turn for model-invoked skills, so every word costs context.
- One line, one sentence when possible.
  State what the skill does and when to use it.
  Put detail in the body, not the description.

Good:

```yaml
description: Create or update a GitHub pull request title and body from the current branch. Use when opening or updating a pull request.
```

Bad:

```yaml
description: >
  Routes GitHub pull request work to the right PR skill.
  Use when opening or updating a pull request.
```

## Self-contained

Keep each skill self-contained. Do not pull in or duplicate guidance from other skills unless:

- the user asks to reference or align with another skill, or
- the skill already references other skills and you are extending that linkage

Do not add provenance or mirroring labels on skill content. Write the rules directly; do not prefix sections with where they came from.

Bad: `Core rules (mirrored from other-skill)`

Reference other skills by name only, in backticks: `skill-name-here`. Do not use file paths (e.g. `.cursor/skills/other-skill/SKILL.md`, `reference.md`).

When the skill lives in a repo, do not reference personal global skills.
The repo and other team members may not have the same global skills you do.
Only reference skills that ship with that repo.

## Numbered steps

Use `1.`, `2.`, ... only for short sequences where each item fits on one line.

When there are too many points, or a single numbered item wraps onto multiple lines, break the sequence into headings instead: `### Step 1`, `### Step 2`, and so on.
Put detail in paragraphs or bullets under each heading.

Good:

```markdown
### Step 1

Confirm scope with the user.
Stop and wait for a reply before continuing.

### Step 2

Write `plan.md` from the confirmed scope.
```

Bad:

```markdown
1. Confirm scope with the user. Stop and wait for a reply before continuing.
2. Write `plan.md` from the confirmed scope.
3. Implement only after the user approves the plan.
4. Run the quality gate before finishing.
5. Update `plan.md` if decisions change during implementation.
```

## User corrections

When the user corrects skill text, update in place:

- State the new guidance only. Remove the old wording.
- Do not restate what was wrong, do not add negations for the prior rule, or keep both old and new versions.

Example: if the skill said use format A and the user wants B, the skill should describe B only. Do not add "do not use A" or a note that it used to be A.
